Hi Jude,

Thanks for raising this. I agree that proper visibility into RECON job execution is important.

Just to reiterate what I mentioned during the discussion earlier today, the RECON tasklet emits deterministic execution logs for every run, including cases where there are no payroll updates in the evaluated window.

For example, during execution the job logs messages such as:

[PayrollRecon] Batch partition processing window: Start={}, End={}
[PayrollRecon] No payroll updates on window {} -> {}
[PayrollRecon] window {}->{} payrolls={} processed={} discrepancies={}

Because of this behavior, the alerting logic can be defined using two clear conditions.

⸻

1. Missing Execution Signal (within 15 minutes)

The RECON job runs hourly, and during each execution it should emit at least one of the [PayrollRecon] logs above. Even when there are no payroll updates, the job still logs the window it evaluated.

Therefore, if none of the expected execution logs appear within 15 minutes of the scheduled run, it would indicate that the job started but did not progress to a valid execution state, which should trigger an alert.

Example Splunk query pattern:

index=<index_name>
"[PayrollRecon]"
| stats latest(_time) as lastSeen
| eval delay=now()-lastSeen
| where delay > 900


⸻

2. Runtime Exception / Job Failure

Independently of the above condition, any runtime exception during job execution should also raise an alert.

Example query:

index=<index_name>
(level=ERROR OR level=FATAL)
(Exception OR error)

or

index=<index_name>
"[PayrollRecon]" AND (Exception OR ERROR)


⸻

So the intended behavior is:

• Valid run with payroll updates → execution log present → no alert
• Valid run with no payroll updates → execution log present → no alert
• Job runs but no execution signal within 15 minutes → alert
• Any runtime exception during execution → alert

This aligns with the behavior discussed earlier today and ensures we avoid false alerts when there are simply no payroll updates to process.

If helpful, I can reproduce both scenarios in the lower environment (a no-data run and a forced exception) so we can validate the alert behavior before enabling it in PROD.

